videnced. The crops through\nout the South are good, and will\naverage more than usual prices.\nRailroad construction will be delayed\nfor some time. This is not due to\nlegislation, but. to the difficulty of\nobtaining money on inflated valua\ntions. Agitation for reduced freight\nrates in the South is being vigorous\nly prosecuted and with some evi\ndence of relief to shippers. The ag\nitation is of a business kind, calm\nand without temper and a disposi\ntion to act on rational grounds. The\nrailroads oppose all efforts to re\nduce rates, but a readjustment of\nthe tariffs enforced in the South is\nenevitable. This process will neces\narily be slow, but its termination\nwill bring greater prosperity to the\npublic and railways alike. It looks\nas though a period of nervous stress\nwas pretty well over and one of re\nnewed cheerfulness was setting in.\nThe equilibrium ha3 been nearly\nreached, but it is not time for re\nnewed speculation. Business con\nservatism is necessary in all finan\ncial calculations. The South is in a\nprosperous condition.\"\nHARD TIMES IN KANSAS.\nThe ol'l days of grasshoppers anil\ndrouth are almost forgotton in the pros\nperous Kansas of to-day; although a\ncitizen of Codell, Earl Shamburg, lias\nnot yet forgotten a hard time he en\ncountered. He says: \"I was worn out\nand discouraged by coughing night and\nday, and could find no relief till I tried\nDr. King's New Discovery. It took\nless than one bottle to completely cure\nme.\" The safest and most reliable\ncough and cold cure and lung and\nthroat healer ever discovered. Guaran\nteed by E. T. Whitehead Co.'s drug\nstore 50c. and $1.00. Trial bottle free.\n\"One of our prominent\" married\ncitizens,\" remarked Uncle Coshall\nHemlock, \"\"commenced last week to\ntalk about affinities in a perfervid\nmanner.\"\n\"And what happened?\"\n\"Other prominent citizens com\nmenced to talk about tar, with a few\nobservations on -the subjects of\nfeathers. This seemed to have the\nrequii-ed effe